WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:02.560
[Music]

00:00:02.560 --> 00:00:04.560
Pushing upwards out of the forest floor

00:00:04.560 --> 00:00:06.400
in the glow of the autumn light, we have:

00:00:06.400 --> 00:00:08.240
a mushroom.

00:00:08.240 --> 00:00:10.426
It shares the forest with the plants
and the animals,

00:00:10.451 --> 00:00:11.454
but it's not a plant

00:00:11.479 --> 00:00:12.684
and it's not an animal.

00:00:12.709 --> 00:00:15.508
It's from an entirely separate
kingdom of life:

00:00:15.533 --> 00:00:18.560
the kingdom of fungi.

00:00:18.560 --> 00:00:20.725
This mushroom is only
one part of this fungus.

00:00:20.750 --> 00:00:23.452
It's the fruiting body
grown for reproduction.

00:00:23.477 --> 00:00:25.420
The rest of this fungus lives hidden

00:00:25.445 --> 00:00:27.680
out of sight, below ground.

00:00:27.680 --> 00:00:30.062
Beneath every mushroom is a fungal network

00:00:30.087 --> 00:00:32.893
of hairlike strands, called a mycelium.

00:00:32.918 --> 00:00:35.512
This is the body of this fungus.

00:00:35.537 --> 00:00:37.040
A mycelium starts its life

00:00:37.040 --> 00:00:38.775
growing from a tiny spore,

00:00:38.800 --> 00:00:41.307
growing in all directions looking for food.

00:00:41.691 --> 00:00:43.358
Then, when the conditions are right,

00:00:43.383 --> 00:00:46.207
it grows a fruiting body out of the ground.

00:00:46.699 --> 00:00:49.746
These fruiting bodies come
in a wide range of different forms,

00:00:49.771 --> 00:00:51.382
but their job is all the same:

00:00:51.407 --> 00:00:55.014
to disperse the spores and
grow the next generation.

00:00:55.039 --> 00:00:58.775
However, only around 10% of fungi
produce mushrooms.

00:00:58.800 --> 00:01:01.600
The kingdom of fungi is wildly diverse:

00:01:01.600 --> 00:01:03.072
from single-celled yeasts

00:01:03.097 --> 00:01:06.721
to pathogenic fungi hijacking
the nervous systems of animals

00:01:06.746 --> 00:01:10.520
to the fungi who form complex
symbiotic relationships with plants.

00:01:10.766 --> 00:01:13.536
We'll explore all this and more
in this map of fungi.

00:01:13.561 --> 00:01:16.019
And like all my maps,
this is available as a poster

00:01:16.044 --> 00:01:18.712
which you can buy from dosmaps.com.

00:01:19.149 --> 00:01:20.960
If we zoom into the microscopic realm,

00:01:20.960 --> 00:01:23.409
we can look closer at a strand of mycelium,

00:01:23.434 --> 00:01:27.157
which is around 5 to 50 times narrower
than a human hair.

00:01:27.182 --> 00:01:30.543
Now, here's a single filament of a mycelium
called a hyphae.

00:01:30.661 --> 00:01:32.533
And here you can see the fungal cells,

00:01:32.558 --> 00:01:34.619
and the cell components within them,

00:01:34.644 --> 00:01:35.808
the organelles.

00:01:35.888 --> 00:01:38.507
And these hyphae,
they grow from their tips,

00:01:38.532 --> 00:01:41.439
sometimes branching out
to grow in different directions.

00:01:41.464 --> 00:01:43.834
But they can also fuse when they meet.

00:01:43.859 --> 00:01:47.024
And this makes the complicated
mycelium network

00:01:47.049 --> 00:01:49.439
that you can kind of see
in the background here.

00:01:49.439 --> 00:01:51.311
Hyphae got tough cell walls

00:01:51.336 --> 00:01:55.087
because they contain a structural polymer
in these walls called chitin.

00:01:55.112 --> 00:01:57.360
And this is the same material
that can be found in

00:01:57.360 --> 00:02:00.339
the exoskeletons of
crustaceans and insects.

00:02:00.364 --> 00:02:03.364
And this cell wall surrounds
a soft plasma membrane.

00:02:03.389 --> 00:02:05.904
This is different to animal cells
which don't have a cell wall;

00:02:05.929 --> 00:02:08.444
they just have
the flexible plasma membrane.

00:02:08.469 --> 00:02:10.959
And this means that animal cells
can ingest their food

00:02:10.959 --> 00:02:13.723
by engulfing it:
Pac-Man style.

00:02:13.748 --> 00:02:15.105
But hyphae can't do this

00:02:15.130 --> 00:02:17.316
because the tough chitin in their cell wall

00:02:17.341 --> 00:02:18.975
means that they're not flexible.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:20.580
They can't engulf any of their food.

00:02:20.605 --> 00:02:23.655
So instead of that, they externally
digest their surroundings,

00:02:23.680 --> 00:02:26.515
doing this by excreting digestive enzymes

00:02:26.540 --> 00:02:27.827
through their cell wall,

00:02:27.852 --> 00:02:30.480
which breaks down the surrounding material

00:02:30.480 --> 00:02:32.905
ready to be absorbed back
through the cell wall

00:02:32.930 --> 00:02:33.967
to feed the hyphae.

00:02:33.992 --> 00:02:37.648
Kind of like their stomach
is on the outside of their bodies.

00:02:37.673 --> 00:02:40.528
Interestingly, another source of food
for some carnivorous fungi

00:02:40.553 --> 00:02:43.760
are the wormlike microorganisms:
nematodes.

00:02:43.760 --> 00:02:46.024
And these fungi have developed
many different techniques

00:02:46.049 --> 00:02:47.588
to catch these nematode worms,

00:02:47.613 --> 00:02:48.800
either with glue traps

00:02:48.800 --> 00:02:50.334
or lassoing them in rings

00:02:50.359 --> 00:02:52.800
or by stunning the nematodes with toxins

00:02:52.825 --> 00:02:54.530
before digesting them.

00:02:54.555 --> 00:02:56.281
Hyphae come in two main types:

00:02:56.305 --> 00:02:57.396
Septate hyphae

00:02:57.421 --> 00:02:59.916
have filaments that are
divided into compartments

00:02:59.941 --> 00:03:01.877
by cross-walls called septa

00:03:01.902 --> 00:03:02.959
which got pores in them

00:03:02.984 --> 00:03:05.390
to let cytoplasm and
some cellular components

00:03:05.414 --> 00:03:06.719
between the cells.

00:03:07.280 --> 00:03:08.719
Coenocytic hyphae

00:03:08.743 --> 00:03:10.730
also known aseptic hyphae

00:03:10.755 --> 00:03:13.395
are fungal filaments
that lack the cross-walls,

00:03:13.420 --> 00:03:16.464
where all the cell organelles
and nuclei are freely flowing.

00:03:16.489 --> 00:03:19.080
Essentially making the entire mycelium

00:03:19.105 --> 00:03:20.993
one giant cell.

00:03:21.534 --> 00:03:23.485
So on a cellular level,
it's really interesting

00:03:23.510 --> 00:03:26.650
that the fact that fungi,
who have got these tough cell walls,

00:03:26.675 --> 00:03:29.219
that explains why
they are the shape they are,

00:03:29.244 --> 00:03:31.020
and why they grow these mycelium networks,

00:03:31.045 --> 00:03:32.640
because being made of

00:03:32.640 --> 00:03:35.861
lots of very thin strands
that all network together

00:03:35.886 --> 00:03:39.115
essentially maximises their surface area

00:03:39.140 --> 00:03:42.204
for trying to digest
whatever they're growing through.

00:03:42.229 --> 00:03:45.200
And a consequence of this is a lot of fungi

00:03:45.200 --> 00:03:46.714
look pretty much exactly the same.

00:03:46.739 --> 00:03:50.404
They're all different kinds of varieties 
of these networks.

00:03:50.429 --> 00:03:52.771
Maybe slightly fatter, slightly thinner.

00:03:52.796 --> 00:03:56.326
I think this might be why fungi 
have historically been under appreciated

00:03:56.351 --> 00:03:58.503
compared to plants and animals.

00:03:58.528 --> 00:04:00.559
When you look at 
different plants or animals,

00:04:00.584 --> 00:04:02.636
you can tell that they're different species

00:04:02.661 --> 00:04:03.698
just by looking at them.

00:04:03.723 --> 00:04:05.596
Their morphologies are different.

00:04:05.621 --> 00:04:08.911
You know, 
that's a squirrel, that's a giraffe.

00:04:08.936 --> 00:04:11.403
But with fungi, unless you're an expert,

00:04:11.428 --> 00:04:13.853
they all look kind of the same.

00:04:13.878 --> 00:04:16.365
But different kinds of fungi 
specialise in breaking down

00:04:16.390 --> 00:04:18.357
different materials for food,

00:04:18.382 --> 00:04:20.713
using a massive range 
of different chemicals

00:04:20.738 --> 00:04:22.139
depending on the species.

00:04:22.164 --> 00:04:26.537
So the diversity of fungi is 
in their chemistry and metabolism

00:04:26.562 --> 00:04:28.159
rather than their shape.

00:04:28.184 --> 00:04:30.960
Historically, people thought 
fungi were a kind of plant

00:04:30.960 --> 00:04:32.593
which kind of makes sense,

00:04:32.618 --> 00:04:34.821
because a lot of fungi grow in the soil,

00:04:34.846 --> 00:04:36.812
they form these sort of networks

00:04:36.836 --> 00:04:37.957
which look a bit like roots

00:04:37.982 --> 00:04:40.525
and they don't move around:
they're not mobile.

00:04:40.550 --> 00:04:42.784
But now we know fungi are actually

00:04:42.808 --> 00:04:45.302
an entirely different kingdom of life,

00:04:45.327 --> 00:04:47.035
separate to plants and animals.

00:04:47.060 --> 00:04:50.720
And they're actually more closely related
to animals than plants.

00:04:50.720 --> 00:04:53.870
Today, the main way to tell the difference
between species of fungus

00:04:53.895 --> 00:04:55.387
is by sequencing their genetics

00:04:55.412 --> 00:04:57.815
using molecular barcoding methods.

00:04:57.840 --> 00:04:59.291
This modern technology has unlocked

00:04:59.316 --> 00:05:01.848
a whole new way to discover and study fungi

00:05:01.873 --> 00:05:05.657
and untangle their evolutionary
relationships between species.

00:05:05.682 --> 00:05:09.488
Mycologists have discovered
about 150,000 species of fungi,

00:05:09.513 --> 00:05:13.599
but they estimate there are 
2 or 3 million species out in nature

00:05:13.624 --> 00:05:15.151
waiting to be discovered

00:05:15.176 --> 00:05:17.686
with potentially very useful 
chemical behaviours

00:05:17.711 --> 00:05:19.774
for new drugs or technologies.

00:05:20.560 --> 00:05:22.844
We'll look at the fascinating 
chemistry of fungi soon,

00:05:22.869 --> 00:05:25.296
but first I need to mention yeast.

00:05:25.321 --> 00:05:26.527
Some species of fungi

00:05:26.552 --> 00:05:29.027
only grow as single-celled yeasts.

00:05:29.052 --> 00:05:31.598
And these reproduce by 
a kind of cell division

00:05:31.623 --> 00:05:33.290
called budding or fission.

00:05:33.315 --> 00:05:36.573
But some fungi can switch between 
living as a yeast or living as a hyphae

00:05:36.598 --> 00:05:39.128
depending on the environment
they find themselves in.

00:05:39.153 --> 00:05:41.120
We also get yeasts living on us,

00:05:41.120 --> 00:05:43.131
which we'll find out about later.

00:05:43.672 --> 00:05:46.289
Fungi are found in just about 
every environment on Earth,

00:05:46.314 --> 00:05:47.963
on land and in the water,

00:05:47.988 --> 00:05:50.413
and they've been found in
extreme environments like deserts

00:05:50.438 --> 00:05:54.101
or areas with high concentrations
of salt or radiation.

00:05:54.126 --> 00:05:58.291
Some can even survive
the intense radiation of space.

00:05:58.316 --> 00:06:01.844
Fungi are essential for the decomposition 
of organic matter,

00:06:01.869 --> 00:06:06.207
breaking it down and cycling the nutrients
back through the environment.

00:06:06.232 --> 00:06:09.664
The organic acids or enzymes hyphae release

00:06:09.689 --> 00:06:11.710
breaks down material as they grow,

00:06:11.735 --> 00:06:14.719
allowing them to grow through
just about any material,

00:06:14.744 --> 00:06:19.694
leaves, soil, wood, rock, even asphalt.

00:06:19.797 --> 00:06:22.800
Deep in the past, 290 million years ago,

00:06:22.800 --> 00:06:24.880
a fungus related to the white rot fungus

00:06:24.880 --> 00:06:26.614
developed special enzymes

00:06:26.639 --> 00:06:28.508
which gave it the ability to break down

00:06:28.533 --> 00:06:31.234
the tough lignin in plant matter.

00:06:31.259 --> 00:06:34.638
Before this, nothing could
break down this tough molecule.

00:06:34.663 --> 00:06:37.680
So, plant matter would just be buried
and compressed over time,

00:06:37.680 --> 00:06:39.557
eventually turning into coal.

00:06:39.582 --> 00:06:43.641
So, a fungus basically stopped
the Earth's production of coal

00:06:43.666 --> 00:06:45.698
290 million years ago.

00:06:46.639 --> 00:06:49.637
Most life on Earth has some kind
of symbiotic relationship

00:06:49.662 --> 00:06:51.542
with some kind of fungi.

00:06:51.567 --> 00:06:53.786
These relationships can be
mutually beneficial

00:06:53.811 --> 00:06:56.809
where both the fungus and the partner
benefit from the relationship.

00:06:56.834 --> 00:06:59.889
For example, leaf cutter ants
are like fungus farmers,

00:06:59.914 --> 00:07:02.465
feeding their fungal gardens with leaves,

00:07:02.490 --> 00:07:05.148
while protecting them from pests and moulds.

00:07:05.173 --> 00:07:08.434
In return, the fungus is a food source
for the ants' larvae.

00:07:09.360 --> 00:07:12.209
Another hugely important
mutually beneficial relationship

00:07:12.234 --> 00:07:15.072
exists between plant roots and fungi.

00:07:15.096 --> 00:07:18.130
This relationship is called mycorrhiza.

00:07:18.155 --> 00:07:21.447
90% of all plants rely on mycorrhiza

00:07:21.472 --> 00:07:23.759
for nutrients like nitrogen and phosphorus

00:07:23.759 --> 00:07:26.018
which fungi extract from the soil.

00:07:26.043 --> 00:07:27.840
And in return, the plant
supplies the fungus

00:07:27.840 --> 00:07:29.707
with food like carbohydrates,

00:07:29.732 --> 00:07:32.542
which the plant produces in photosynthesis.

00:07:33.199 --> 00:07:36.168
There are two main kinds of mycorrhiza.

00:07:36.193 --> 00:07:40.248
Arbuscular mycorrhiza
penetrate the plant's root cells

00:07:40.273 --> 00:07:41.840
to exchange nutrients.

00:07:41.840 --> 00:07:45.778
Whereas ectomycorrhiza
penetrate between the plant cells

00:07:45.803 --> 00:07:47.116
but not inside them.

00:07:47.553 --> 00:07:50.020
Interestingly, the mycelium network
of a fungus

00:07:50.045 --> 00:07:52.117
can connect to multiple different plants

00:07:52.142 --> 00:07:54.126
through their mycorrhiza.

00:07:54.151 --> 00:07:55.983
And this is called
a mycorrhizal network

00:07:56.008 --> 00:08:00.287
and this effectively connects plants
to each other through their roots,

00:08:00.312 --> 00:08:03.815
potentially giving them a route to
exchange information with each other.

00:08:03.840 --> 00:08:08.057
So, some studies suggest that plants
can give each other warnings

00:08:08.082 --> 00:08:10.654
if they're being attacked
by insects or pathogens,

00:08:10.679 --> 00:08:14.136
or they can even transfer
resources to each other,

00:08:14.161 --> 00:08:17.350
if one is, you know, not doing so well.

00:08:17.375 --> 00:08:19.676
But I should say this is still
an active area of research

00:08:19.701 --> 00:08:21.508
and there's still some debate
about how much

00:08:21.533 --> 00:08:24.398
plants use this mechanism
to communicate with each other.

00:08:24.423 --> 00:08:25.423
I should also say that

00:08:25.448 --> 00:08:28.208
these mycorrhiza aren't always
mutually beneficial.

00:08:28.233 --> 00:08:31.008
Some fungi can switch
to a pathogenic mode

00:08:31.033 --> 00:08:32.595
where they're leeching off the plant,

00:08:32.620 --> 00:08:36.126
or they can just be commensal
and not really do anything.

00:08:37.074 --> 00:08:38.438
Now let's look at lichens

00:08:38.463 --> 00:08:40.463
which are made of
a combination of fungi

00:08:40.488 --> 00:08:43.144
along with algae or cyanobacteria

00:08:43.168 --> 00:08:45.815
all living in a
symbiotic relationship.

00:08:45.840 --> 00:08:48.731
Lichens are really important
because they're the first organisms

00:08:48.756 --> 00:08:50.658
to establish themselves
in a new environment

00:08:50.683 --> 00:08:52.339
like when a glacier retreats

00:08:52.364 --> 00:08:55.435
or when volcanic rock covers an area.

00:08:55.467 --> 00:08:57.839
They contribute to soil formation

00:08:57.839 --> 00:09:01.607
by breaking down rock
and adding nutrients to the soil.

00:09:01.632 --> 00:09:05.171
Fungi have also been found 
living harmlessly inside plants.

00:09:05.196 --> 00:09:06.643
These are known as endophytes

00:09:06.668 --> 00:09:10.547
and can live inside a plant
for all or just part of their life cycles.

00:09:10.572 --> 00:09:12.715
Some endophytes
may even help the host plant

00:09:12.740 --> 00:09:13.762
by enhancing growth

00:09:13.787 --> 00:09:16.222
or helping tolerate stresses
like drought

00:09:16.247 --> 00:09:19.433
or increase the resistance
to insects or pathogens.

00:09:19.458 --> 00:09:22.328
But of course, many fungi
are pathogens themselves.

00:09:22.353 --> 00:09:25.344
Although plants have got
many beneficial relationships with fungi,

00:09:25.369 --> 00:09:28.737
by far the most common
and damaging pathogens

00:09:28.762 --> 00:09:31.673
that plants face,
are also fungi.

00:09:31.698 --> 00:09:33.040
They're far more damaging

00:09:33.040 --> 00:09:36.320
than viruses, bacteria, or even insects.

00:09:36.320 --> 00:09:38.620
Pathogenic fungal infections
can damage plants

00:09:38.645 --> 00:09:40.050
by destroying cells,

00:09:40.075 --> 00:09:42.640
blocking the vascular tissues
that carry water,

00:09:42.640 --> 00:09:43.871
releasing toxins,

00:09:43.896 --> 00:09:48.102
and growing over leaves,
stopping them from photosynthesising.

00:09:48.127 --> 00:09:50.817
Rusts, smuts, moulds, and mildews

00:09:50.842 --> 00:09:53.920
are all common names
for fungal plant pathogens,

00:09:53.920 --> 00:09:57.887
which can cause major losses
to crop yields worldwide.

00:09:57.912 --> 00:10:00.491
Hundreds of billions of dollars
worth of wheat and barley

00:10:00.516 --> 00:10:01.639
are lost each year

00:10:01.663 --> 00:10:04.298
because of Fusarium graminearum.

00:10:04.323 --> 00:10:07.415
And in the 1950s, an entire
species of banana was wiped out

00:10:07.440 --> 00:10:10.998
by the related species called
Fusarium oxysporum.

00:10:11.023 --> 00:10:13.491
And this is now threatening
the modern variety, too.

00:10:14.174 --> 00:10:17.821
And wood imported from Asia is thought
to be the origin of Dutch elm disease

00:10:17.846 --> 00:10:20.082
which has wiped out most of the elm trees

00:10:20.107 --> 00:10:22.480
in temperate Europe and North America.

00:10:22.480 --> 00:10:26.399
There are countless other examples of
fungal pathogens that prey on plants.

00:10:26.399 --> 00:10:28.640
But they also infect animals too,

00:10:28.640 --> 00:10:31.040
sometimes in the most ghoulish ways.

00:10:31.040 --> 00:10:33.874
These are called entomogenous fungi.

00:10:33.899 --> 00:10:37.788
The zombie ant fungus,
Ophiocordyceps unilateralis,

00:10:37.813 --> 00:10:41.171
infects ants by piercing
the exoskeleton with enzymes

00:10:41.196 --> 00:10:44.167
and spreads fungal cells
throughout the body.

00:10:44.192 --> 00:10:46.713
It then secretes special
neurological compounds

00:10:46.738 --> 00:10:49.617
that hijack the ant's
central nervous system,

00:10:49.642 --> 00:10:51.838
forcing it to climb high into a tree

00:10:51.863 --> 00:10:54.133
and lock its mandibles onto a leaf

00:10:54.158 --> 00:10:55.214
with a death grip.

00:10:55.843 --> 00:10:59.054
This makes a nice stable platform
for the fungus to grow a fruiting body

00:10:59.079 --> 00:11:01.408
to disperse spores in a large area

00:11:01.433 --> 00:11:03.189
to infect more hosts.

00:11:03.753 --> 00:11:05.557
This is the kind of crazy biology

00:11:05.582 --> 00:11:08.000
that inspired the zombies
in The Last of Us.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:09.089
And they're not alone.

00:11:09.114 --> 00:11:11.230
There are many different pathogenic fungi

00:11:11.255 --> 00:11:15.040
that infect other insects and spiders.

00:11:15.040 --> 00:11:16.819
But there is a really positive side

00:11:16.844 --> 00:11:19.383
to this fascinating biochemistry.

00:11:19.408 --> 00:11:21.516
When a fungus infects an arthropod,

00:11:21.541 --> 00:11:24.800
it needs to suppress
the immune system of its host.

00:11:24.800 --> 00:11:27.942
So it secretes immunosuppressing chemicals.

00:11:27.967 --> 00:11:32.386
And fortunately, these chemical compounds
also work in humans

00:11:32.411 --> 00:11:34.111
and have been developed into drugs

00:11:34.136 --> 00:11:36.833
that make organ transplantation possible.

00:11:36.858 --> 00:11:38.871
This is just one of a host of drugs

00:11:38.896 --> 00:11:40.494
that have been developed from fungi

00:11:40.518 --> 00:11:42.243
and their complex biochemistry.

00:11:42.268 --> 00:11:44.353
In fact, fungi arguably produce

00:11:44.378 --> 00:11:47.138
some of the most important drugs
ever discovered.

00:11:47.878 --> 00:11:49.038
They include statins,

00:11:49.063 --> 00:11:51.839
which are a group of fungal chemicals
extracted from a mould,

00:11:51.839 --> 00:11:54.314
which have been found to interfere
with fat production

00:11:54.339 --> 00:11:55.519
and have been synthesised

00:11:55.519 --> 00:11:58.664
to treat high cholesterol
and cardiovascular diseases.

00:11:59.369 --> 00:12:02.130
In the wild, fungi fight with each other
for resources.

00:12:02.155 --> 00:12:06.421
So, drugs that come from fungi have also
been shown to treat fungal infections.

00:12:06.446 --> 00:12:08.788
They've also been shown to inhibit viruses,

00:12:08.813 --> 00:12:11.612
have anti-tumour compounds
used in cancer treatments.

00:12:11.637 --> 00:12:13.588
They've also been used in vaccines,

00:12:13.613 --> 00:12:15.994
and are used as a treatment for MS.

00:12:16.637 --> 00:12:19.910
But arguably the biggest impact
of fungi on medicine

00:12:19.934 --> 00:12:22.858
is their ability to kill bacteria.

00:12:22.883 --> 00:12:25.474
The first modern antibiotic, penicillin,

00:12:25.498 --> 00:12:27.391
was first used in 1930

00:12:27.415 --> 00:12:30.504
to treat an eye infection
in newborn babies.

00:12:30.529 --> 00:12:33.985
But it only found widespread use
at the end of the Second World War

00:12:34.009 --> 00:12:35.916
when scientists finally figured out

00:12:35.941 --> 00:12:39.106
how to synthesise it on mass
using fermentation.

00:12:39.839 --> 00:12:42.431
This was the beginning
of the antibiotic revolution.

00:12:42.456 --> 00:12:45.689
And since then, hundreds of millions
of lives have been saved

00:12:45.714 --> 00:12:49.145
because of antibiotics
derived from fungi.

00:12:50.264 --> 00:12:54.676
Now, there's a very good reason
why fungi produce antibacterial compounds.

00:12:54.701 --> 00:12:58.207
They often live side by side
and compete for food and space.

00:12:58.232 --> 00:13:02.310
So fungi produce antibiotic compounds
as a natural defence mechanism,

00:13:02.335 --> 00:13:05.533
to kill bacteria or inhibit their growth.

00:13:05.558 --> 00:13:08.111
And because fungi
digest their food externally,

00:13:08.136 --> 00:13:10.738
excreting digestive enzymes
outside their body

00:13:10.763 --> 00:13:12.163
to break down their food,

00:13:12.187 --> 00:13:15.200
they then need to protect that food
from other organisms

00:13:15.200 --> 00:13:16.587
while they absorb it.

00:13:16.889 --> 00:13:19.347
This is amazing footage showing bacteria

00:13:19.372 --> 00:13:22.242
swimming in the liquid surrounding hyphae.

00:13:22.267 --> 00:13:24.047
These have been called fungal highways

00:13:24.072 --> 00:13:28.240
and are probably essential
for healthy soil.

00:13:28.240 --> 00:13:30.705
In fact, fungi release many other compounds

00:13:30.730 --> 00:13:32.160
for attack and defence,

00:13:32.160 --> 00:13:33.692
feeding, communication,

00:13:33.717 --> 00:13:36.253
and other functions
we don't yet understand.

00:13:37.360 --> 00:13:39.279
Because of their amazing biochemistry,

00:13:39.279 --> 00:13:42.160
we found many other uses for fungi.

00:13:42.160 --> 00:13:43.875
They're used in bioremediation

00:13:43.900 --> 00:13:46.560
by breaking down insecticides, herbicides,

00:13:46.560 --> 00:13:48.959
and other pollutants like crude oil,

00:13:48.959 --> 00:13:50.637
polyurethane plastics,

00:13:50.662 --> 00:13:53.600
even explosive TNT.

00:13:53.600 --> 00:13:57.841
They may even be useful for bioremediation
of radioactively polluted sites

00:13:57.866 --> 00:14:00.534
as they've got the ability
to absorb heavy metals

00:14:00.559 --> 00:14:03.600
including radioactive material.

00:14:03.600 --> 00:14:05.440
They've also been used in agriculture,

00:14:05.440 --> 00:14:07.222
for biological control of pests

00:14:07.246 --> 00:14:11.074
like locusts which threaten food harvests.

00:14:11.099 --> 00:14:12.959
And they're used extensively to produce

00:14:12.959 --> 00:14:15.040
industrial chemicals like acids,

00:14:15.040 --> 00:14:17.686
detergents and ethanol, amongst others.

00:14:17.711 --> 00:14:22.183
60% of enzymes used in industry
are generated by fungi.

00:14:22.208 --> 00:14:26.877
And all of the citric acid
used in soft drinks is made by fungi.

00:14:26.902 --> 00:14:30.867
And the strong mycelium can be used
to build materials and textiles

00:14:30.892 --> 00:14:33.920
to replace plastics and leathers.

00:14:33.920 --> 00:14:37.386
Because of their ability to concentrate
nutrients from within the soil,

00:14:37.411 --> 00:14:41.630
fungi are an excellent source of food
for us and many other animals.

00:14:41.655 --> 00:14:43.836
Today, the global market for edible fungi

00:14:43.861 --> 00:14:46.772
is worth about 32 billion pounds

00:14:46.797 --> 00:14:52.034
with about 350 species of fungi
collected or cultivated for food.

00:14:52.059 --> 00:14:54.535
Foraging for mushrooms is a fun activity,

00:14:54.560 --> 00:14:57.146
but there is a risk of poisoning.

00:14:57.171 --> 00:15:00.258
Although surprisingly,
few fungi are truly toxic.

00:15:00.283 --> 00:15:05.738
Only 120 out of 22,000 mushroom
producing species could kill you.

00:15:05.763 --> 00:15:07.911
The problem is several
of these deadly varieties

00:15:07.935 --> 00:15:10.008
look very similar to edible mushrooms,

00:15:10.033 --> 00:15:12.660
making it easy to make a fatal mistake.

00:15:12.685 --> 00:15:16.422
And some fungal poisons
are heat stable, too.

00:15:16.447 --> 00:15:20.064
So, the mushroom stays poisonous
even after you cook it.

00:15:20.089 --> 00:15:24.031
The purpose of these toxic chemical
compounds is still being figured out,

00:15:24.056 --> 00:15:26.607
but they're likely to be
a deterrent and defence

00:15:26.631 --> 00:15:31.839
against the mushroom being eaten before
it's completed the job of producing spores.

00:15:31.839 --> 00:15:34.002
Some of the defensive chemicals
that fungi produce

00:15:34.027 --> 00:15:36.065
have a psychotropic effect,

00:15:36.090 --> 00:15:38.684
notably psilocybin in magic mushrooms.

00:15:38.709 --> 00:15:43.274
And also LSD was first derived
from the urgot fungus.

00:15:43.299 --> 00:15:46.575
In all, around 150
mushroom producing species

00:15:46.600 --> 00:15:48.527
have got hallucinogenic properties.

00:15:48.552 --> 00:15:51.035
And despite these species also being toxic,

00:15:51.060 --> 00:15:55.224
human consumption of these fungi
goes back at least 3,000 years.

00:15:55.249 --> 00:15:59.590
And have formed the basis for
a number of ancient cultural rituals.

00:15:59.615 --> 00:16:02.212
In the clinical setting,
psychotropics are being studied

00:16:02.237 --> 00:16:05.936
for their potential in treating
chronic depression and PTSD.

00:16:05.961 --> 00:16:08.109
These studies appear to show
that psilocybin

00:16:08.134 --> 00:16:10.959
causes a temporary increase
in communication

00:16:10.959 --> 00:16:13.759
between different parts of the brain.

00:16:13.759 --> 00:16:17.406
But fungi provide us with more
than just  mushrooms for food.

00:16:17.431 --> 00:16:20.826
Humans have been using yeast
to preserve or ferment food and drinks

00:16:20.851 --> 00:16:23.519
for over 10,000 years.

00:16:23.519 --> 00:16:25.519
Fermentation is a metabolic pathway

00:16:25.519 --> 00:16:28.480
yeast uses in oxygen limited conditions

00:16:28.480 --> 00:16:30.800
to break down sugars and generate energy

00:16:30.800 --> 00:16:33.939
producing byproducts
like ethanol and carbon dioxide

00:16:33.964 --> 00:16:37.043
as well as many other compounds
like phenols and esters

00:16:37.068 --> 00:16:40.153
which produce the delicious
flavours and smells.

00:16:40.178 --> 00:16:42.129
Fermentation is used in baking bread,

00:16:42.154 --> 00:16:45.479
brewing beer, wine,
and many other alcoholic drinks,

00:16:45.504 --> 00:16:48.365
and can also be used
in a number of other fermented foods

00:16:48.390 --> 00:16:51.466
like tofu, soy sauce, chocolate, coffee,

00:16:51.491 --> 00:16:53.513
and some types of yogurt and cheese,

00:16:53.538 --> 00:16:55.524
amongst many others.

00:16:55.549 --> 00:16:57.250
But while we're feeding on fungi,

00:16:57.275 --> 00:16:59.064
there are fungi feeding on us.

00:16:59.088 --> 00:17:01.860
Humans host a staggering variety of fungi,

00:17:01.885 --> 00:17:03.779
mostly in a commensal relationship

00:17:03.804 --> 00:17:06.819
where they do neither harm nor good to us.

00:17:06.844 --> 00:17:10.692
For instance, the basidiomycete yeast
Malassezia

00:17:10.717 --> 00:17:13.081
is a natural inhabitant of human skin

00:17:13.106 --> 00:17:16.102
where it feeds off the oils in sebum
in our sebaceous glands

00:17:16.127 --> 00:17:17.991
and tends to thrive in teenagers

00:17:18.016 --> 00:17:21.616
when puberty increases
the production of these oils.

00:17:21.641 --> 00:17:26.283
While usually harmless, Malassezia
is associated with several skin conditions

00:17:26.308 --> 00:17:28.578
including dandruff amongst others.

00:17:28.603 --> 00:17:32.466
And other dermaphytes can cause
other conditions, like athletes foot.

00:17:32.491 --> 00:17:34.730
However, while we can coexist
with these fungi

00:17:34.754 --> 00:17:36.608
without giving them a second thought,

00:17:36.633 --> 00:17:39.657
under the right conditions,
they can quickly become pathogens,

00:17:39.681 --> 00:17:41.437
causing our bodies harm.

00:17:41.462 --> 00:17:44.318
On our body, we also have
species of Candida,

00:17:44.343 --> 00:17:46.683
which normally don't cause us any harm.

00:17:46.708 --> 00:17:48.856
But they're also opportunistic pathogens,

00:17:48.881 --> 00:17:52.320
affecting mucous membranes
and causing thrush.

00:17:52.320 --> 00:17:55.344
Usually, fungal infections are only
really a nuisance to humans

00:17:55.368 --> 00:17:56.441
who are otherwise healthy.

00:17:56.466 --> 00:18:00.707
But they can cause serious complications
if they're already ill.

00:18:01.463 --> 00:18:03.360
When it comes to reproduction,

00:18:03.360 --> 00:18:05.652
fungi are again quite unusual,

00:18:05.677 --> 00:18:09.825
because many of them can reproduce
both sexually and asexually.

00:18:09.850 --> 00:18:13.547
This means they can either find a partner
to mix genes with to make new offspring,

00:18:13.572 --> 00:18:15.630
or they can just clone themselves.

00:18:15.654 --> 00:18:18.037
Although plants can do this as well.

00:18:18.062 --> 00:18:19.200
The advantage of cloning

00:18:19.200 --> 00:18:20.526
is that it's very quick:

00:18:20.551 --> 00:18:22.133
just simple cell division.

00:18:22.157 --> 00:18:26.400
But sexual reproduction
improves diversity within a population,

00:18:26.400 --> 00:18:28.929
which is an advantage
over asexual reproduction,

00:18:28.954 --> 00:18:32.160
to explore more ecological niches.

00:18:32.160 --> 00:18:35.095
Interestingly, while many fungi
have got two sexes,

00:18:35.120 --> 00:18:36.196
like us humans,

00:18:36.220 --> 00:18:40.434
some fungi can have hundreds
to thousands of different sexes.

00:18:40.459 --> 00:18:42.409
They all look the same,
but the fungi are able to

00:18:42.434 --> 00:18:44.376
chemically detect
the sex of a neighbour

00:18:44.401 --> 00:18:45.828
and if they're compatible or not.

00:18:45.853 --> 00:18:48.079
And scientists have built
a massive spreadsheet

00:18:48.104 --> 00:18:50.541
to keep track of who can
get it on with who.

00:18:51.679 --> 00:18:55.995
All fungi disperse themselves
by producing microscopic spores.

00:18:56.020 --> 00:18:59.704
But these spores vary massively
in shape, size, and colour.

00:18:59.729 --> 00:19:01.632
The size, shape, and features of spores

00:19:01.657 --> 00:19:05.760
are built to take advantage of
many different methods of dispersal.

00:19:05.760 --> 00:19:08.499
Primitive fungi have whip-like tails,
called flagella,

00:19:08.523 --> 00:19:11.095
to disperse through watery environments.

00:19:11.120 --> 00:19:12.693
Others disperse in the air

00:19:12.718 --> 00:19:15.419
from the gills
on the undersides of mushrooms.

00:19:15.444 --> 00:19:18.400
Others are rejected at great speeds
from the fruiting bodies.

00:19:18.400 --> 00:19:21.265
And others are specifically adapted
to be picked up or eaten

00:19:21.289 --> 00:19:23.194
by insects, birds, or mammals.

00:19:23.218 --> 00:19:26.293
Like truffles, whose fruiting bodies
grow below ground,

00:19:26.318 --> 00:19:27.800
but communicate with the above world

00:19:27.825 --> 00:19:29.856
by releasing a special aroma

00:19:29.881 --> 00:19:31.543
that attracts mammals.

00:19:31.567 --> 00:19:33.732
Something we enjoy as well.

00:19:33.757 --> 00:19:37.215
The aroma is the sex pheromones
of male pigs...

00:19:37.240 --> 00:19:39.366
Delightful...

00:19:39.391 --> 00:19:41.817
Probably the least known effect of fungi
in the environment

00:19:41.842 --> 00:19:44.737
is their role in the formation
of clouds and rains.

00:19:44.762 --> 00:19:47.895
As fungal spores can trigger
the formation of water droplets,

00:19:47.920 --> 00:19:51.417
causing rains which land
on the tree canopy or forest floor

00:19:51.442 --> 00:19:54.227
and this helps maintain
the forest microclimate.

00:19:55.774 --> 00:19:57.678
Finally, evolution.

00:19:57.703 --> 00:20:00.154
This is our current picture
of the fungal tree of life

00:20:00.179 --> 00:20:02.993
which contains eight main branches.

00:20:03.018 --> 00:20:05.603
We think the earliest fungi evolved
around a billion years ago,

00:20:05.628 --> 00:20:07.623
and were simple single-celled organisms

00:20:07.648 --> 00:20:09.246
that lived in the sea.

00:20:09.270 --> 00:20:12.172
As mentioned before,
one of the key signatures of a fungus

00:20:12.196 --> 00:20:15.023
is containing chitin in their cell walls.

00:20:15.048 --> 00:20:16.519
This can be difficult to detect,

00:20:16.543 --> 00:20:18.357
but detailed studies have shown that

00:20:18.382 --> 00:20:22.082
downy mildews, and water moulds,
and slime moulds

00:20:22.107 --> 00:20:23.238
don't have chitin,

00:20:23.262 --> 00:20:25.090
and so aren't fungi.

00:20:25.122 --> 00:20:29.048
But the single-celled
Cryptomycota and Microsporidia do,

00:20:29.073 --> 00:20:31.223
making them the fungi that exist today

00:20:31.248 --> 00:20:34.278
that most resemble
the earliest forms of fungi.

00:20:34.303 --> 00:20:37.679
They're also exclusively parasites.

00:20:37.679 --> 00:20:41.887
These along with
Blastocladiomycota and Chytridiomycota

00:20:41.912 --> 00:20:45.302
reproduce using a mobile spore
with a whip-like tail,

00:20:45.326 --> 00:20:46.433
called a flagellum.

00:20:46.458 --> 00:20:48.260
Which allows them to move through water,

00:20:48.285 --> 00:20:50.752
just like a human sperm cell.

00:20:50.777 --> 00:20:53.379
This mobile spore was lost
when fungi moved onto the land

00:20:53.403 --> 00:20:55.180
around 700 million years ago,

00:20:55.205 --> 00:20:59.047
and then evolved the other ways
of dispersing spores.

00:20:59.072 --> 00:21:03.402
Zoopagomycota are almost exclusively
pathogens or parasites

00:21:03.427 --> 00:21:06.125
which infect or feed off
plants or animals,

00:21:06.150 --> 00:21:10.240
or they live within plants or animals
without harming them.

00:21:10.240 --> 00:21:13.705
Mucoromycota are known for forming
relationships with plants

00:21:13.730 --> 00:21:16.545
that are mutually beneficial
to the plant and fungi.

00:21:16.570 --> 00:21:19.765
This group contains the subphylum
Glomeromycota

00:21:19.789 --> 00:21:21.795
which forms the micorrhizal relationships

00:21:21.819 --> 00:21:25.808
with about 80% of land plants
including most crops.

00:21:25.833 --> 00:21:28.480
They also harbour a large diversity
of bacteria

00:21:28.480 --> 00:21:31.840
that live inside the fungal cells.

00:21:31.840 --> 00:21:35.239
And finally,
the Ascomycota and Basidiomycota

00:21:35.263 --> 00:21:38.662
which together forms the
subkingdom Dikarya.

00:21:38.687 --> 00:21:41.750
Ascomycets are commonly known
as the sac fungi,

00:21:41.775 --> 00:21:45.249
and include morels, truffles,
brewer's and baker's yeasts,

00:21:45.274 --> 00:21:48.668
as well as the majority
of fungal symbionts in lichens.

00:21:48.693 --> 00:21:51.707
Whereas Basidiomycets
are perhaps the most familiar to us,

00:21:51.732 --> 00:21:55.905
as they contain the fungi
who grow into the majority of mushrooms.

00:21:55.930 --> 00:21:58.220
So that's an overall view
of the world of fungi,

00:21:58.244 --> 00:21:59.998
visualised in this map.

